<slide><h2>Proliferation of Languages</h2>
<p> Making a web site <strong>active</strong> requires a server-side language:
</p>
<div align=center>
C<br />
C + PERL<br />
C + PERL + MetaHTML<br />
C + PERL + MetaHTML + PHP3 + ASP + Java<br />
C + PERL + MetaHTML + PHP3 + ASP + Java + JSP + DSSSL + XSLT + PIA<br />
...
</div>
<p align="right"> There is no sign of consolidation,<br />
but new languages mostly look like XML.
</p>
</slide>

<slide><h2>Increasing Use of XML</h2>
<p> Perhaps the one area of convergence:
</p>
<ul>
  <li> XML is a standardized syntax
  </li>
  <li> ... with no associated semantics
  </li>
  <li> Good for:
       <ul>
	 <li> text with markup
	 </li>
	 <li> data
	 </li>
       </ul>
  </li>
  <li> Easy for computers to read and write
  </li>
  <li> not so easy for humans,
  </li>
  <li> ... but the tools are getting better
  </li>
</ul>
</slide>


<slide><h2>Proliferation of Clients</h2>
<ul>
  <li> More and more browsers
       <ul>
	 <li> each new version is <em>very</em> different
	 </li>
	 <li> many old versions still around
	 </li>
       </ul>
  </li>
  <li> Not just browsers
       <ul>
	 <li> ``Thin'' clients
	 </li>
	 <li> Mobile clients
	 </li>
	 <li> Specialized applications
	 </li>
       </ul>
  </li>
</ul>
</slide>

<slide><h2>Increasing Collaboration</h2>
<ul>
  <li> Many people work on a web application
       <ul>
	 <li> ...over time
	 </li>
	 <li> ...at the same time
	 </li>
       </ul>
  </li>
  <li> Some have specialized skills
       <ul>
	 <li> writers
	 </li>
	 <li> artists
	 </li>
	 <li> application designers
	 </li>
	 <li> web designers
	 </li>
	 <li> program designers
	 </li>
       </ul>
  </li>
</ul>
</slide>

<slide><h2>Increasing Customization and Interaction</h2>
<ul>
  <li> Web applications are ``just'' documents<br />
       ... and so are easy to edit
  </li>
  <li> End users have many skills, <br />
       ... but web application design not usually one of them
  </li>
  <li> Some web applications are <em>designed for interaction</em>.
       <ul>
	 <li> news sites
	      (e.g. <a href="http://www.linuxtoday.com/">Linux Today</a>)
	 </li>
	 <li> discussion sites
	      (e.g. <a href="http://slashdot.org/">Slashdot</a>)
	 </li>
	 <li> collaborative writing
	      (e.g. <a href="http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?WikiWikiWeb">Wiki Wiki
	      Web</a>) 
	 </li>
       </ul>
  </li>
</ul>
</slide>

<slide><h2>Proliferation of Development Environments</h2>
<ul>
  <li> From ``notepad'' and <code>emacs</code>
  </li>
  <li> ... to integrated HTML editors
  </li>
  <li> ... ... to publishing frameworks
  </li>
       <p> 
       </p>
  <li> Different developers have different preferences
  </li>
  <li> Customizing and interacting users may have simpler needs<br />
       ... or they may be computer experts themselves.
  </li>
</ul>
</slide>


<slide><h2>Shifting Balance; Wider Range</h2>
<ul>
  <li> Much processing is moving to the server
  </li>
  <li> ... but clients are getting more capable
  </li>
  <li> Server-side languages are proliferating
  </li>
  <li> ... but the new ones are all based on XML
  </li>
  <li> Developers are getting more skilled
  </li>
  <li> ... but end users are doing more customization
  </li>
</ul>
</slide>


<slide><h2>Requirements for Web Applications</h2>
<ul>
  <li> Cross Platform 
  </li>
  <li> Client Neutral
  </li>
  <li> Scalable
  </li>
  <li> Stable Interfaces
       <ul>
	 <li> interfaces must not change if implementation changes.
	 </li>
       </ul>
  </li>
  <li> Customizable
  </li>
</ul>
</slide>

<slide><h2>Requirements for Application Development</h2>
<ul>
  <li> Support wide range of skill levels
       <ul>
	 <li> allow customization by non-experts
	 </li>
       </ul>
  </li>
  <li> Strong support for markup languages (XML, HTML)
  </li>
  <li> Support for distributed development
  </li>
  <li> Platform neutral
  </li>
  <li> Tool neutral
       <ul>
	 <li> support for adding new tools
	 </li>
	 <li> tools should preserve source-level formatting
	 </li>
       </ul>
  </li>
</ul>
</slide>

